ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic performances of the as-synthesized ZnO2/CQD composites towards TC degradation were shown in Fig. 5
                        a. In the dark, the adsorption–desorption equilibrium between TC and photocatalysts could achieved within 1 h. Interestingly, the adsorption capacities of all ZnO2/CQD composites were much higher than that of individual ZnO2 and CQD (Fig. S4), which demonstrated that CQD modification significantly improved the adsorption performance of ZnO2. After 4 h of visible-light irradiation, pure CQD could hardly degrade TC (Fig. S4), and individual ZnO2 could degrade around 81 % of TC due to the self-sensitization effect of TC [40–42]. Compared with CQD and ZnO2 alone, all ZnO2/CQD composites showed the enhanced photocatalytic performance to a certain degree. Even a small dosage of CQD (0.05 mL) was added, the degradation efficiency of TC could reach 83 % within 3 h. Increasing the dosage from 0.05 to 0.5 mL, the degradation efficiency was gradually improved, and over 80 % of TC could be degraded by ZnO2/CQD-0.5 after 2 h of light irradiation, which outperformed other reported visible-light photocatalysts (Table 1
                        ). However, the degradation efficiency was slightly decreased when the dosage of CQD was further raised to 1 mL, which might be due to the shield effect of excessive CQD [43]. Thus, ZnO2/CQD-0.5 was selected for TC degradation in the subsequent experiments. In addition, the common pseudo-zero, pseudo-first and pseudo-second order kinetic models were employed to fit the experimental data of TC degradation, and the results were shown in Fig. 5b and Fig. S5. Obviously, the pseudo-second order kinetic model with higher linear correlation coefficient (Table S2) was more suitable than other two kinetics models to describe the processes of TC photocatalytic degradation by ZnO2/CQD composites.
